2021 Narrative:
"Since the beginning of 2022, FAO has successfully initiated a number of assessments and surveys aimed to inform evidence based humanitarian programming, including response to strengthen food and nutrition security and support agriculture and livestock based livelihoods. 
Assessments and surveys completed to date (June 2022):
- In March 2022 FAO Afghanistan launched the fourth round of household survey through the Data in Emergencies Monitoring (DIEM-Monitoring) System to monitor the impacts of shocks on agriculture livelihoods and food security utilizing a random sample of 5971 households in 25 provinces. The findings, country brief, story map and dashboard published in May 2022 is available on DIEM website Afghanistan: DIEM ‚Äì Data in Emergencies Monitoring brief, round 4 (fao.org).
- FAO along with WFP and other national and international NGOs conducted the Integrated Food Security Phase Classification (IPC) analysis between published in May 2022. (Afghanistan: Humanitarian assistance averted a food security catastrophe in the harsh winter months, but hunger persists at unprecedented levels (fao.org))
